         <div>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="1"
                xml:id="pb-1"
                facs="#i1"/>
            <lb/>
1<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology Lect<hi rend="superscript">e</hi> 6.</hi>
            <lb/>
1811.<lb/>
Most of the changes that now<lb/>
take place in the solid parts of the Earth<lb/>
except those produced by volcanic fires<lb/>
were discussed in the last lecture. I<lb/>
shall now ask permission to direct your<lb/>
attention to this part of the subject, which<lb/>
demands an extensive discussion.<lb/>
To persons who inhabit countries, happily<lb/>
not liable to these grand &amp; awful operations,<lb/>
they may appear rather as <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">accidents</hi> than<lb/>
as <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">essential events</hi> in the order of things -<lb/>
But their extent, their constancy, &amp; the<lb/>
ultimate tendency of their effects lead<lb/>
to a very different conclusion; &amp;<lb/>
inevitably prove to us, their importance<lb/>
their efficacy, &amp; even their utility in the<lb/>
great series of the phenomena of Nature<lb/>
Volcanic fires have operated to a<lb/>
great extent in all quarters of the Globe,<lb/>
&amp; they appear to have occurred in the<lb/>
earliest ages of which we have any<lb/>
authentic records. -<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#person_842"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag1" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Pindar</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> who lived nearly 500<lb/>
years before the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Christian</hi> Era mentions<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Eruptions of <rs xml:id="ttag2" ref="#place_184" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag2" type="place">
          Etna
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi> &amp; blending the<lb/>
description of this great <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">event</del> natural event<lb/>
with poetic fable, he attributes the effect<lb/>
to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#misc_375"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag3">
                  <hi rend="underline">Typheus</hi>
               </term>
            </rs> who after being defeated<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="2"
                xml:id="pb-2"
                facs="#i2"/>
            <lb/>
by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#person_843"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag4" type="person">
          Jupiter
        </name>
            </rs> in the wars of the Gods<lb/>
&amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#misc_425"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag5">
          Titans
        </term>
            </rs> was supposed in the ancient<lb/>
mythology to have been buried<lb/>
under <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#place_569"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="place">
          Sicily
        </name>
            </rs>. -<lb/>
The passage is one of the finest in<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Odes</hi> - I shall read a few lines<lb/>
of it in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#otherwork_223"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag7">
            West's translation
        </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
- "Now under Sulphurous Cumas sea seabound Coast<lb/>
And vast <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag8"
                ref="#place_569"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag8" type="place">
          Sicilia
        </name>
            </rs>, lies his shaggy breast<lb/>
By snowy <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag9"
                ref="#place_184"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag9" type="place">
          Etna
        </name>
            </rs> nurse of endless frost<lb/>
The Eternal prop of heaven for ever fresh<lb/>
Forth from whose nitrous caverns issuing, rise<lb/>
Pure liquid fountains of tempestuous fire<lb/>
And veil in ruddy mists the noon day skies<lb/>
Whilst clothed in smoke the eddying flames aspire." -<lb/>
- In South <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag10"
                ref="#place_878"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag10" type="place">
          America
        </name>
            </rs>, in the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag11"
                ref="#misc_402"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag11">
                  <hi rend="underline">Cordilleras</hi>
               </term>
            </rs> the highest <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Mountain Chain</hi>
            <lb/>
belonging to the Earth, a number of<lb/>
Volcanoes now exist in a state of<lb/>
activity. In <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag12"
                ref="#place_877"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag12" type="place">
          Japan
        </name>
            </rs>, in<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag13"
                ref="#place_1007"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag13" type="place">
          Kamschatka
        </name>
            </rs> &amp; in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag14"
                ref="#place_237"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag14" type="place">
          Iceland
        </name>
            </rs>, a<lb/>
great part of the surface has been<lb/>
formed or modified by the agency<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Volcanic Fires</hi>. In <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag15"
                ref="#place_569"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag15" type="place">
          Sicily
        </name>
            </rs>, &amp;<lb/>
in a number of the Islands of the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag16"
                ref="#place_1191"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag16" type="place">
          mediterranean
        </name>
            </rs> Sea, their effects are<lb/>
equally visible. -<lb/>
- A terrible eruption of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#place_184"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag17" type="place">
          Etna
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
is recorded by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
                ref="#person_844"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag18" type="person">
          Thucydides
        </name>
            </rs> to have<lb/>
taken place 476 years before <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag19"
                ref="#person_951"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag19" type="person">
          Christ
        </name>
            </rs>,<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="3"
                xml:id="pb-3"
                facs="#i3"/>
            <lb/>
&amp; long anterior to this time "Its summit<lb/>
crowned with snows, emitting flame" had<lb/>
been celebrated by the Greek poets.<lb/>
- In <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag20"
                ref="#place_097"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag20" type="place">
          Italy
        </name>
            </rs> &amp; the South of France a<lb/>
considerable portion of the Country exhibits<lb/>
proofs of ancient Volcanoes. Vesuvius<lb/>
as we learn from <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag21"
                ref="#person_448"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag21" type="person">
          Diodorus Siculus
        </name>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag22"
                ref="#person_510"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag22" type="person">
          Strabo
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
was overspread with ashes before the first<lb/>
recorded Eruption in the 79<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">th</hi> year after<lb/>
 the Christian Era. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag23"
                ref="#place_714"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag23" type="place">
          Herculaneum
        </name>
            </rs> a City<lb/>
buried by that event &amp; since partly uncovered<lb/>
is found built of Lava. - Even <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag24"
                ref="#place_155"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag24" type="place">
          Rome
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
itself proudly called by its ancient<lb/>
inhabitants the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Eternal City</hi>, - (as would<lb/>
appear from the testimony of an excellent<lb/>
mineralogist) is founded upon the<lb/>
ruins of an extinguished Volcano. And<lb/>
many of the beautiful &amp; fertile hills<lb/>
&amp; Vallies of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag25"
                ref="#place_1261"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag25" type="place">
          Auvergne
        </name>
            </rs>, &amp; the Vivarais<lb/>
are said to owe their rich &amp; abundant<lb/>
soils to decomposing Lava. -<lb/>
- The subject is extensive &amp;<lb/>
sublime - It can hardly fail to<lb/>
excite curiosity in all minds attached<lb/>
to the knowledge of Nature &amp; it possesses<lb/>
numerous relation to the general Theory<lb/>
of the Earth. - |_ It affords the only<lb/>
known <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">facts of the agency</hi> of Heat upon<lb/>
rocks that occur on a great scale.<lb/>
It exhibits to us the grandest of the<lb/>
operations of Natural Chemistry; &amp; it<lb/>
offers a rich &amp; as yet almost an<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">untouched</hi> field of discovery. -<lb/>
- Till within the last few years,<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Volcanoes</hi> had been merely a matter<lb/>
of wonder &amp; vague narration - &amp;<lb/>
had little occupied the attention<lb/>
of philosophical Persons. - <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag26"
                ref="#person_699"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag26" type="person">
          Sir<lb/>William Hamilton
        </name>
            </rs> may be said to have<lb/>
been the first accurate observer<lb/>
of the Phenomena. - His<lb/>
magnificent work on the "Phlegraean<lb/>
fields" is well known, it equally<lb/>
demonstrates the extent of his knowledge<lb/>
&amp; the refinement of his Taste. - It<lb/>
affords the true &amp; picturesque<lb/>
Character of a great Volcanic region<lb/>
and the illustrations are the productions<lb/>
of an elegant &amp; acute mind. -<lb/>
The path pointed out by our<lb/>
celebrated Countryman was immediately<lb/>
followed by <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">a</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">an able</add> Philosopher, <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of whom</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in a former lecture I made honorable</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">mention</del>; by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag27"
                ref="#person_300"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag27" type="person">
          Dolomieu
        </name>
            </rs>. - In<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag28"
                ref="#otherwork_225"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag28">
            his work "Sur les isles Ponces"
        </bibl>
            </rs> the<lb/>
most minute observations may be<lb/>
found combined with the most<lb/>
enlarged views. &amp; the Author<lb/>
has enlightened his Geological researches<lb/>
by the assistance of the most refined<lb/>
methods of Chemistry known in his<lb/>
time. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
5<lb/>
2<lb/>
The last Edition of the philosophical<lb/>
Travels into <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag29"
                ref="#place_1168"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag29" type="place">
          Campania
        </name>
            </rs> Scip. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag30"
                ref="#person_820"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag30" type="person">
          Breislac
        </name>
            </rs> is likewise<lb/>
an excellent work. The mineralogical<lb/>
details are admirable, the descriptions are<lb/>
animated and allowed by those who<lb/>
have followed his steps to be peculiarly<lb/>
accurate - To this book I shall<lb/>
occasionally refer - it is replete with new<lb/>
&amp; useful information. -<lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag31"
                ref="#otherwork_227"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag31">
            The work of D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Van Troil on<lb/>Iceland
        </bibl>
            </rs> &amp; the letters published by<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag32"
                ref="#person_845"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag32" type="person">
          Sir John Stanley
        </name>
            </rs> in the Transactions of<lb/>
the Royal Society of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag33"
                ref="#place_284"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag33" type="place">
          Edinburgh
        </name>
            </rs> offer<lb/>
admirable details on some of the most<lb/>
curious objects of a most interesting Volcanic<lb/>
district |_ &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag34"
                ref="#otherwork_228"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag34">
            the letters on the hot Springs
        </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
are highly worth of perusal, not merely<lb/>
on account of the excellent Scientific<lb/>
details which they contain, but likewise<lb/>
on account of the elegant &amp; vivid<lb/>
descriptions of some of the most peculiar<lb/>
&amp; magnificent phenomena in Nature<lb/>
|_ The forms of Volcanic Mountains<lb/>
in cases when they have been actually<lb/>
produced or covered by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Lava</hi>, are<lb/>
usually conical - They are<lb/>
generally more steep, &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">abrupt</hi>, towards<lb/>
the summit, than primary or secondary<lb/>
Mountains. &amp; their tops present<lb/>
a pointed &amp; irregular outline. -<lb/>
- The Rocks that constitute the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
exterior bases of Volcanic Mountains, &amp;<lb/>
which have not been altered by fire,<lb/>
differ very much in species in different<lb/>
Countries &amp; their nature is in no<lb/>
way connected with the changes taking<lb/>
place in the interior, &amp; lower regions<lb/>
of the district. -<lb/>
|_  - The seat of volcanic fires is deep<lb/>
in the bosom of the Earth - &amp; they have<lb/>
often broken out amidst primary as<lb/>
well as Secondary strata. -<lb/>
- |_  The Rocks that appear at the foot<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag35"
                ref="#place_169"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag35" type="place">
                  <hi rend="underline">Vesuvius</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> are principally <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag36" ref="#chemical_184" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag36">
          Shell Limestone
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>.<lb/>
The foundations of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag37"
                ref="#place_184"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag37" type="place">
          Etna
        </name>
            </rs> are said to be<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag38"
                ref="#chemical_092"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag38">
          Granite
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag39"
                ref="#chemical_125"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag39">
          Porphyry
          
        </term>
            </rs> - &amp; these substances<lb/>
according to the reports of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag40"
                ref="#person_271"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag40" type="person">
          Humboldt
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
constitute the base of the great Volcanic<lb/>
Chain of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag41"
                ref="#place_177"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag41" type="place">
          Andes
        </name>
            </rs>, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">some of the eminencies</hi>
            <lb/>
of which are elevated to the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">enormous</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">height</hi> of four miles above the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">level</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the Sea</hi>.<lb/>
- The lower region of the Volcanic<lb/>
Mountains, even when the substratum<lb/>
of the soil is Lava, are usually<lb/>
exceedingly fertile &amp; when a long<lb/>
continued quiet has prevailed in the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">interior</hi>, vegetation is vigorous,<lb/>
upon all parts of the surface, that<lb/>
are not raised above the line of<lb/>
perpetual snow.<lb/>
- Even in the dreary Climate of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag42"
                ref="#place_1007"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag42" type="place">
          Kamschatka
        </name>
            </rs>, the lowlands, in the<lb/>
Summer Months are clothed with <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">grass</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">&amp; with trees</hi>, Soon as the snows have<lb/>
disappeared, the warmth of the Sun acting<lb/>
upon soil produced by the decomposed Volcanic<lb/>
matter, covers it with verdure; &amp; by far<lb/>
the most fertile parts of this wild &amp; desolate<lb/>
Country are those situated in the neighbourhood<lb/>
of Subterranean fires. -<lb/>
- In <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mild &amp; temperate</hi> Climates, the<lb/>
fact is still more striking: &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
